    "review-wip-reviewer-60537": {
      "status": "complete",
      "findings": 2,
      "findings_details": [
        {
          "file": "client/src/hooks/useNeedsInputState.ts",
          "line": 41,
          "severity": "medium",
          "category": "correctness",
          "title": "mountedRef never reset to true \u2014 silently drops initial seed in React StrictMode",
          "body": "mountedRef is initialized to true (line 41) but the useEffect cleanup sets it to false (line 69) and never resets it. In React 18 StrictMode (dev), effects run twice: mount -> cleanup -> remount. After the first cleanup, mountedRef.current is false. The second mount's refresh() call completes the fetch, hits the guard at line 50 (if result.ok && mountedRef.current), and silently skips setMap. The initial seed from GET /api/terminals is dropped on the second StrictMode mount \u2014 the hook appears correctly seeded in prod but shows count=0 on first render in dev. Fix: add mountedRef.current = true; at the top of the useEffect body (line 59), before void refresh(), so each mount cycle rearms the guard. This pattern is established in react/issues \u2014 the ref should track the current mount's lifecycle, not the component instance lifecycle.",
          "confidence": "high"
        },
        {
          "file": "client/src/hooks/useNeedsInputState.ts",
          "line": 85,
          "severity": "nit",
          "category": "performance",
          "title": "count derivation not memoized \u2014 spread+filter on every render",
          "body": "count: [...map.values()].filter(Boolean).length runs inline on every render (line 85). It allocates an array and iterates all entries even when the consumer only needs count and nothing else changed. For the typical map size (<100 branches) this is negligible, but it is unnecessarily eager. Wrapping in useMemo with [map] as the dependency would make the cost proportional to map changes rather than parent re-renders: const count = useMemo(() => [...map.values()].filter(Boolean).length, [map]). This is a nit \u2014 the current code is not wrong, just slightly wasteful.",
          "confidence": "high"
        }
      ]
    },
